        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Identifying the Bottleneck First"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RAG latency has four distinct stages: embedding the query, retrieving from the vector store, reranking candidates, and generating the answer. The dominant term varies by deployment \u2014 for small corpora with a fast ANN index, generation dominates; for large corpora with a cross-encoder reranker, reranking can exceed everything else. Optimizing the wrong stage wastes engineering effort. Instrument each stage with timestamps before applying any optimization technique."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "RAG latency budget breakdown and optimization levers",
          "title": "Four-stage latency budget with corresponding optimization strategies"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Profiling the Pipeline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Wrap each stage in a timer and log the deltas. Even a simple `time.perf_counter()` wrapper gives enough signal to identify the bottleneck. Once you know which stage dominates, apply targeted optimizations rather than trying to improve everything at once."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import time\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n\n@dataclass\nclass LatencyProfile:\n    embed_ms: float = 0.0\n    retrieve_ms: float = 0.0\n    rerank_ms: float = 0.0\n    generate_ms: float = 0.0\n\n    @property\n    def total_ms(self) -> float:\n        return self.embed_ms + self.retrieve_ms + self.rerank_ms + self.generate_ms\n\n    def dominant_stage(self) -> str:\n        stages = {\n            \"embed\": self.embed_ms,\n            \"retrieve\": self.retrieve_ms,\n            \"rerank\": self.rerank_ms,\n            \"generate\": self.generate_ms,\n        }\n        return max(stages, key=stages.get)\n\ndef profiled_rag(query: str, embedder, retriever, reranker, llm) -> tuple[str, LatencyProfile]:\n    profile = LatencyProfile()\n\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n    q_emb = embedder.embed_query(query)\n    profile.embed_ms = (time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000\n\n    t1 = time.perf_counter()\n    docs = retriever.invoke(query)\n    profile.retrieve_ms = (time.perf_counter() - t1) * 1000\n\n    t2 = time.perf_counter()\n    ranked = reranker.compress_documents(docs, query) if reranker else docs\n    profile.rerank_ms = (time.perf_counter() - t2) * 1000\n\n    t3 = time.perf_counter()\n    context = \"\\n\\n\".join(d.page_content for d in ranked[:3])\n    answer = llm.invoke(f\"Context:\\n{context}\\n\\nQuestion: {query}\")\n    profile.generate_ms = (time.perf_counter() - t3) * 1000\n\n    return answer, profile"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Async and Parallel Retrieval"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If you retrieve from multiple sources (dense vector store + sparse BM25 + structured database), running them sequentially adds their latencies. Switching to `asyncio.gather()` runs all retrievals concurrently and waits only for the slowest one. For single-source retrieval, batching the embedding step and using the vector store's batch search endpoint (where available) reduces per-query overhead."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom langchain_core.documents import Document\n\nasync def async_retrieve(query: str, retrievers: list) -> list[Document]:\n    \"\"\"Retrieve from multiple sources in parallel; merge and deduplicate.\"\"\"\n    tasks = [r.ainvoke(query) for r in retrievers]\n    results = await asyncio.gather(*tasks, return_exceptions=True)\n\n    seen, docs = set(), []\n    for batch in results:\n        if isinstance(batch, Exception):\n            continue  # one slow source doesn't block others\n        for doc in batch:\n            key = doc.page_content[:64]\n            if key not in seen:\n                seen.add(key)\n                docs.append(doc)\n    return docs\n\n# LCEL chain with async retrieval\nfrom langchain_core.runnables import RunnableLambda\n\nasync def parallel_rag(query: str, retrievers, llm) -> str:\n    docs = await async_retrieve(query, retrievers)\n    context = \"\\n\\n\".join(d.page_content for d in docs[:5])\n    return await llm.ainvoke(f\"Context:\\n{context}\\n\\nQuestion: {query}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Faster Vector Search with HNSW and Quantization"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Flat L2 (brute-force) search scales O(n) with corpus size. FAISS HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World) delivers approximate nearest-neighbor search in O(log n) time with recall typically above 95%. Product Quantization (PQ) compresses 768-dimensional float32 embeddings from 3 KB to 96 bytes per vector, enabling a 100M-vector index to fit in ~9 GB RAM instead of 300 GB. Use `IndexHNSWFlat` as a baseline and add `IndexIVFPQ` for large corpora."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import faiss\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef build_hnsw_index(embeddings: np.ndarray, m: int = 32) -> faiss.IndexHNSWFlat:\n    \"\"\"HNSW index \u2014 fast approximate search with high recall.\"\"\"\n    d = embeddings.shape[1]\n    index = faiss.IndexHNSWFlat(d, m)      # m = number of edges per node\n    index.hnsw.efConstruction = 200        # higher = better recall at build time\n    index.hnsw.efSearch = 64               # higher = better recall at query time\n    index.add(embeddings.astype(\"float32\"))\n    return index\n\ndef build_ivfpq_index(embeddings: np.ndarray,\n                       n_lists: int = 256,\n                       m_subvectors: int = 8) -> faiss.IndexIVFPQ:\n    \"\"\"IVF+PQ \u2014 best for corpora > 1M vectors; trades recall for memory.\"\"\"\n    d = embeddings.shape[1]\n    quantizer = faiss.IndexFlatL2(d)\n    # m_subvectors \u00d7 8 bits \u2192 each embedding compressed to m_subvectors bytes\n    index = faiss.IndexIVFPQ(quantizer, d, n_lists, m_subvectors, 8)\n    index.train(embeddings.astype(\"float32\"))\n    index.add(embeddings.astype(\"float32\"))\n    index.nprobe = 16   # how many IVF buckets to search; higher = better recall\n    return index\n\ndef search(index, query_emb: np.ndarray, top_k: int = 10) -> tuple:\n    D, I = index.search(query_emb.reshape(1, -1).astype(\"float32\"), top_k)\n    return D[0], I[0]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lightweight Reranking Strategies"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Full cross-encoder reranking scores every (query, passage) pair with a BERT-class model \u2014 expensive at 200\u2013400 ms for top-20 candidates. Three strategies reduce this cost: (1) apply the cross-encoder to only top-5 candidates (already roughly sorted by dense retrieval); (2) use a BM25 pre-filter to cut the candidate set from 100 to 20 before dense reranking; (3) replace the cross-encoder with ColBERT late-interaction scoring, which pre-computes passage token embeddings offline and reduces online cost to a few dot products."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain.retrievers.document_compressors import CrossEncoderReranker\nfrom langchain_community.cross_encoders import HuggingFaceCrossEncoder\n\ndef build_fast_reranker(top_n: int = 5):\n    \"\"\"Cross-encoder applied to top-5 only \u2014 limits latency to ~40ms.\"\"\"\n    model = HuggingFaceCrossEncoder(model_name=\"cross-encoder/ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2\")\n    return CrossEncoderReranker(model=model, top_n=top_n)\n\n# BM25 pre-filter reduces cross-encoder input from 100 \u2192 20 candidates\nfrom langchain_community.retrievers import BM25Retriever\n\ndef hybrid_retriever_with_prefilter(corpus: list, dense_retriever,\n                                     dense_k: int = 20, bm25_k: int = 20):\n    bm25 = BM25Retriever.from_texts([d.page_content for d in corpus], k=bm25_k)\n\n    def retrieve(query: str):\n        dense = dense_retriever.invoke(query)[:dense_k]\n        sparse = bm25.invoke(query)\n        # Union, then cross-encode only the intersection + top overlap\n        combined = {d.page_content: d for d in dense + sparse}\n        return list(combined.values())[:20]  # max 20 \u2192 cross-encoder\n\n    return retrieve"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Streaming and Prompt Compression"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Even after minimizing retrieval latency, the Time to First Token (TTFT) can still feel slow if the LLM processes a large context before generating output. Two techniques help: streaming tokens to the client as they are generated (LangChain's `astream_events` or OpenAI's `stream=True`), and compressing the retrieved context with LLMLingua before passing it to the LLM. LLMLingua prunes low-perplexity tokens from passages \u2014 typically reducing context length by 50\u201380% with less than 3% quality degradation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain_core.runnables import RunnableParallel, RunnablePassthrough\nfrom langchain_core.output_parsers import StrOutputParser\nfrom langchain_openai import ChatOpenAI\n\n# Streaming LCEL chain\nllm = ChatOpenAI(model=\"gpt-4o-mini\", streaming=True)\n\nasync def streaming_rag(query: str, retriever, prompt_template):\n    docs = retriever.invoke(query)\n    context = \"\\n\\n\".join(d.page_content for d in docs[:4])\n    chain = prompt_template | llm | StrOutputParser()\n\n    # Yield tokens as they arrive \u2014 TTFT < 500ms for most queries\n    async for chunk in chain.astream({\"context\": context, \"question\": query}):\n        yield chunk   # pass to WebSocket / SSE endpoint\n\n# LLMLingua context compression\nfrom llmlingua import PromptCompressor\n\ncompressor = PromptCompressor(\n    model_name=\"microsoft/llmlingua-2-xlm-roberta-large-meetingbank\",\n    use_llmlingua2=True,\n)\n\ndef compress_context(passages: list[str], ratio: float = 0.5) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Compress passages to ~50% of original token count before LLM call.\"\"\"\n    full_context = \"\\n\\n\".join(passages)\n    result = compressor.compress_prompt(full_context, rate=ratio, force_tokens=[\".\"])\n    return result[\"compressed_prompt\"]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Connection Pooling and Batch Embedding"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each query requires one embedding call to your model server. Under concurrent load, establishing a new HTTP connection per request wastes 20\u201350 ms in TLS handshake overhead. Use an async HTTP client with a persistent connection pool (httpx `AsyncClient` with `limits`), and batch queries from multiple concurrent requests into a single embed call when the model API supports it. The embedding server processes a batch of 32 queries nearly as fast as a single query, so batching amortizes the round-trip cost across users."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import httpx\nimport asyncio\nfrom collections import defaultdict\n\n# Persistent connection pool \u2014 reuse TLS connections across requests\nhttp_client = httpx.AsyncClient(\n    base_url=\"https://api.openai.com\",\n    limits=httpx.Limits(max_connections=50, max_keepalive_connections=20),\n    timeout=10.0,\n)\n\n# Batching embedder \u2014 collects queries for N ms before firing\nclass BatchEmbedder:\n    def __init__(self, flush_interval_ms: float = 10.0, max_batch: int = 32):\n        self._queue: list[tuple[str, asyncio.Future]] = []\n        self._flush_interval = flush_interval_ms / 1000\n        self._max_batch = max_batch\n        self._lock = asyncio.Lock()\n\n    async def embed(self, query: str) -> list[float]:\n        loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()\n        fut: asyncio.Future = loop.create_future()\n        async with self._lock:\n            self._queue.append((query, fut))\n            if len(self._queue) >= self._max_batch:\n                await self._flush()\n        # Small wait to allow more requests to batch together\n        await asyncio.sleep(self._flush_interval)\n        async with self._lock:\n            if not fut.done():\n                await self._flush()\n        return await fut\n\n    async def _flush(self):\n        batch = self._queue[:self._max_batch]\n        self._queue = self._queue[self._max_batch:]\n        queries = [q for q, _ in batch]\n        # Single API call for the whole batch\n        resp = await http_client.post(\n            \"/v1/embeddings\",\n            json={\"input\": queries, \"model\": \"text-embedding-3-small\"},\n            headers={\"Authorization\": \"Bearer ...\"},\n        )\n        data = resp.json()[\"data\"]\n        for (_, fut), item in zip(batch, data):\n            fut.set_result(item[\"embedding\"])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adaptive Reranking \u2014 Skip When Dense Scores Are Confident"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Dense retrieval assigns each passage a similarity score. When the top-1 score is much higher than the top-2 (e.g., gap > 0.15), the ranking is already decisive and a cross-encoder reranker will rarely change the outcome. Skipping the reranker in these high-confidence cases saves 150\u2013300 ms with no quality loss. Only invoke the reranker when the top-k scores are clustered closely together \u2014 that is where reranking provides the most lift."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain_core.documents import Document\n\ndef adaptive_rerank(query: str,\n                    docs_with_scores: list[tuple[Document, float]],\n                    reranker,\n                    confidence_gap: float = 0.15,\n                    top_k: int = 5) -> list[Document]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Skip cross-encoder reranking when the top dense score is clearly dominant.\n    docs_with_scores: [(doc, cosine_similarity), ...] sorted descending\n    \"\"\"\n    if not docs_with_scores:\n        return []\n\n    scores = [s for _, s in docs_with_scores]\n    top_score = scores[0]\n    second_score = scores[1] if len(scores) > 1 else 0.0\n\n    if (top_score - second_score) >= confidence_gap:\n        # Dense ranking is decisive \u2014 no reranking needed\n        return [d for d, _ in docs_with_scores[:top_k]]\n\n    # Scores are close \u2014 apply cross-encoder to resolve ordering\n    docs = [d for d, _ in docs_with_scores[:20]]\n    return reranker.compress_documents(docs, query)[:top_k]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimization Techniques at a Glance"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Different techniques address different stages and come with different trade-offs. Use this as a decision guide after profiling your pipeline."
          }
        ]
      },
